05353nam a22008535i 9781400852659DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2014    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008526597 a10.1515/97814008526592doi  a(DE-B1597)454041  a(OCoLC)984650503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDS149 7aHIS0190002bisacsh 7aSOC0480002bisacsh 7aSOC0490002bisacsh04a320.540956942231 aGribetz, Jonathan, eauthor.10aDefining Neighbors :bReligion, Race, and the Early Zionist-Arab Encounter /cJonathan Gribetz.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliterations -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. Locating the Zionist-Arab Encounter: Local, Regional, Imperial, and Global Spheres -- tCHAPTER 2. Muhammad Ruhi al-Khalidi's "as-Sayūnīzm": An Islamic Theory of Jewish History in Late Ottoman Palestine -- tCHAPTER 3. "Concerning Our Arab Question"? Competing Zionist Conceptions of Palestine's Natives -- tCHAPTER 4. Imagining the "Israelites": Fin de Siècle Arab Intellectuals and the Jews -- tCHAPTER 5. Translation and Conquest: Transforming Perceptions through the Press and Apologetics -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter  aAs the Israeli-Palestinian conflict persists, aspiring peacemakers continue to search for the precise territorial dividing line that will satisfy both Israeli and Palestinian nationalist demands. The prevailing view assumes that this struggle is nothing more than a dispute over real estate. Defining Neighbors boldly challenges this view, shedding new light on how Zionists and Arabs understood each other in the earliest years of Zionist settlement in Palestine and suggesting that the current singular focus on boundaries misses key elements of the conflict.Drawing on archival documents as well as newspapers and other print media from the final decades of Ottoman rule, Jonathan Gribetz argues that Zionists and Arabs in pre-World War I Palestine and the broader Middle East did not think of one another or interpret each other's actions primarily in terms of territory or nationalism. Rather, they tended to view their neighbors in religious terms-as Jews, Christians, or Muslims-or as members of "scientifically" defined races-Jewish, Arab, Semitic, or otherwise. Gribetz shows how these communities perceived one another, not as strangers vying for possession of a land that each regarded as exclusively their own, but rather as deeply familiar, if at times mythologized or distorted, others. Overturning conventional wisdom about the origins of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, Gribetz demonstrates how the seemingly intractable nationalist contest in Israel and Palestine was, at its start, conceived of in very different terms.Courageous and deeply compelling, Defining Neighbors is a landmark book that fundamentally recasts our understanding of the modern Jewish-Arab encounter and of the Middle East conflict today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJewish-Arab relations. 0aPalestinian ArabsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical sciencexEssays. 0aPolitical sciencexGovernmentxGeneral. 0aPolitical sciencexGovernmentxNational. 0aPolitical sciencexReference. 0aZionismxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97